Les deux Pologne
The European Parliament recently condemned the Polish government's attempt to deprive Bronislaw Geremek of his parliamentary mandate.
An old Solidarity leader, a former political prisoner, and a former Minister for Foreign Affairs - who led Poland's NATO accession - Geremek refused to sign another new declaration stating that he was not an agent of the secret police during the communist era.
European parliamentarians spoke of a "witch hunt" regarding the behavior of the Polish government, and Geremek declared that the lustration law [denazification/denazification] poses a threat to public liberties.
In response, Polish Prime Minister Jaroslaw Kaczynski accused him of "harming the motherland" and of fostering anti-Polish sentiments.
The communists used the same words when Geremek criticized their abuse of power.
A constitutional court decision from May 11 largely invalidated the lustration law, allowing Geremek to retain his seat in the European Parliament at least for now.
But this law fits into the broader policy framework of the Polish government aimed solely at weakening the institutions and democratic fabric of the country.
What is happening in Poland, where the collapse of communism began?
Every revolution goes through two phases: first a fight for freedom, then a struggle for power.
The first is an emancipation of the human soul through which man expresses what is best within him, while the second liberates the worst: envy, intrigues, greed, suspicion, and the desire for revenge.
The revolution triggered by the Polish trade union Solidarity followed an unusual trajectory.
Solidarity, forced into secrecy when martial law was decreed in December 1981, survived seven years of repression to reappear in the open in 1989, in the wake of Gorbachev's "perestroika."
In the negotiations that brought an end to the communist regime, Solidarity and the reformist wing of the communist government arrived at a compromise that opened the way for the peaceful dismantling of communist dictatorship throughout the Soviet bloc.
Solidarity adopted a compromising stance rather than one of revenge, preferring the idea of a Poland for all rather than a country divided between all-powerful winners and oppressed losers.
Since 1989, there have been changes in government, but the country has remained stable. The former communists themselves have accepted the rules of parliamentary democracy and market economy.
But not everyone has followed this path.
Today, Poland is governed by a coalition of post-Solidarity revenge-seeking forces, post-communist provincial disruptors, xenophobic and anti-Semitic groups, heirs of pre-war chauvinism, and circles around Radio Maryja, the voice of ethnic-clerical fundamentalism.
There are worrying signs everywhere: the authority of Justice is undermined, the independence of the Constitutional Court is questioned, civil servants are bought off, and the role of the prosecutor is politicized.
Every day, social life is subjected to repressive regulation.
Why all this?
Every successful revolution has its winners and losers.
The Polish revolution brought public freedoms, but also more crime, a market economy but also the risks of bankruptcy for businesses and high unemployment, as well as the emergence of a dynamic middle class, accompanied by a widening income gap.
It opened Poland to Europe, but it also induced fear of foreigners and fear of a mass Western cultural invasion.
For the losers of the 1989 Polish revolution, freedom comes with a lot of uncertainties.
In large corporations, Solidarity workers have become the victims of the freedoms they won.
In the communist prison universe, people were considered to belong to the state, but it took care of them.
In a world of freedom, nobody takes care of us.
It is in this atmosphere of anxiety that the existing coalition governs, combining the conservative potion of George Bush with Vladimir Putin's centralism.
Solidarity veterans thought that the end of the dictatorship would allow them to reach the heavens.
But among the communists, the guilty were not punished, and the virtuous Solidarity activists were not rewarded.
As a result, a feeling of injustice gave rise to resentment, envy, and a vengeful energy directed not only at old enemies but also at old friends who seemed to be profiting from the situation.
The losers did not want to acknowledge that the conquest of freedom was Poland's greatest success in 300 years.
To them, Poland remained a country governed by the communist security apparatus.
This Poland needed a moral revolution that would ensure that crimes were not left unpunished, virtue was rewarded, and injustices were rectified.
After their victory in the 2005 general elections, the losing political parties chose a method: a large purge.
According to preliminary estimates, the lustration process is expected to take 17 years and affect 700,000 people.
A list of names was found in the security services' archives; it will be made public.
The 700,000 people slated for lustration must declare that they did not collaborate with the security services.
Those who refuse or make false declarations must be fired and banned from practicing their profession for ten years.

The cardinal Dziwisz from Kraków reminds us that there is no room "for revenge, vengeance, lack of respect for human dignity, and baseless accusations."
Never since the fall of communism has a cardinal used such strong words.
Should this cleansing have taken place at the beginning of Poland's transformation? The aim of this peaceful revolution was freedom, sovereignty, and economic reforms, not a hunt for suspects, whether proven or not, who had belonged to the secret police.
If such a hunt had been organized in 1990, neither Leszek Balcerowicz's economic reforms nor the establishment of the rule of law would have been possible.
And Poland would not be a member of either NATO or the European Union.
Today, two Poles are facing each other.
The Poland of suspicion, fear, and revenge fights against the Poland of hope, courage, and dialogue.
This Poland - one of openness and tolerance, that of John Paul II and Czesław Miłosz, of my friends from the underground and the prison - must prevail.
I believe that the Poles will once again defend their right to be treated with dignity.
The constitutional court's decision leaves hope that the second phase of the Polish revolution will destroy neither what gave birth to it, the will for freedom, nor what it has produced, a democratic state.
